    "rationale": "This example shows the oxidation of a simple, acyclic primary alcohol (1-pentanol) to the corresponding aldehyde (pentanal). This is a classic textbook transformation for the Pfitzner-Moffatt oxidation. The reagents listed are dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) as the oxidant, dicyclohexylcarbodiimide (DCC) as the activator, and pyridinium trifluoroacetate as the essential mild acid catalyst. The simple aliphatic substrate avoids potential side reactions or ambiguities with other named reactions.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a simple primary alcohol, avoiding complex structures, unsaturation, or aromatic rings that could trigger other named reaction queries (e.g., Swern, Parikh-Doering, Corey-Kim, Oppenauer). The specific combination of DMSO, a carbodiimide (DCC), and a mild acid catalyst is characteristic of the Pfitzner-Moffatt protocol, distinguishing it from other DMSO-based oxidations."
  }
